concept_explanation.creating_threads:
**Three ways to create a thread:**

**Method 1: Extend Thread** (simple but limited — can't extend anything else)
```java
class MyTask extends Thread {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Running in: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
    }
}

MyTask t = new MyTask();
t.start();  // starts the thread; run() executes in a new thread
```

**Method 2: Implement Runnable** (preferred — keeps class hierarchy free)
```java
class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Running in: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
    }
}

Thread t = new Thread(new MyRunnable());
t.start();
```

**Method 3: Lambda (Java 8+)** — most concise, most common in modern code:
```java
Thread t = new Thread(() -> {
    System.out.println("Running in: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
});
t.start();

// Even shorter for single expression:
Thread t = new Thread(() -> System.out.println("Hello from thread!"));
t.start();
```

**Best practice**: prefer Runnable (Method 2/3) over extending Thread (Method 1). Runnable separates the TASK from the THREAD that runs it — cleaner design.

concept_explanation.non_determinism:
**Thread execution is NON-DETERMINISTIC:**

```java
for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    int task = i;
    new Thread(() -> System.out.println("Task " + task)).start();
}

// Possible outputs (ALL are valid):
// Run 1: Task 0, Task 1, Task 2
// Run 2: Task 2, Task 0, Task 1
// Run 3: Task 1, Task 2, Task 0
// Run 4: Task 0, Task 2, Task 1
```

The OS scheduler decides which thread runs when. You don't control the order.

**Why non-deterministic?**
- Multiple CPU cores can run threads truly simultaneously
- The OS preempts threads at arbitrary moments
- System load, other processes, memory pressure all affect scheduling

**This is fundamental** — non-determinism is the source of both the power AND the complexity of threads. Topics 10.2-10.4 teach how to write correct concurrent code despite non-determinism.

concept_explanation.thread_sleep_and_join:
**`Thread.sleep(ms)`** — pause the CURRENT thread:

```java
System.out.println("Start");
try {
    Thread.sleep(1000);  // pause for 1 second
} catch (InterruptedException e) {
    Thread.currentThread().interrupt();  // restore interrupt flag — best practice
}
System.out.println("After 1 second");
```

`sleep()` throws checked `InterruptedException` — always handle it!

**`thread.join()`** — wait for a thread to finish:

```java
Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(500);
    System.out.println("t1 done");
});

t1.start();
System.out.println("Waiting for t1...");
t1.join();   // main thread blocks until t1 completes
System.out.println("t1 has finished");

// Output (guaranteed order):
// Waiting for t1...
// t1 done
// t1 has finished
```

**join() with timeout**: `t1.join(2000)` — wait at most 2 seconds, then continue regardless.

concept_explanation.thread_naming_and_info:
**Thread naming and metadata:**

```java
// Get the current thread:
Thread current = Thread.currentThread();
System.out.println(current.getName());  // 'main' in main()

// Name a thread:
Thread t = new Thread(() -> {
    System.out.println("I am: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
});
t.setName("WorkerThread-1");
t.start();
// Output: I am: WorkerThread-1

// Thread priority (1=lowest, 10=highest, 5=default):
t.setPriority(Thread.MAX_PRIORITY);  // 10
t.setPriority(Thread.NORM_PRIORITY); // 5 (default)
t.setPriority(Thread.MIN_PRIORITY);  // 1
// Priority is a HINT to the scheduler — not guaranteed

// Daemon threads — shut down when main thread exits:
Thread daemon = new Thread(() -> {
    while (true) { /* background task */ }
});
daemon.setDaemon(true);  // must set BEFORE start()
daemon.start();
// JVM exits even if daemon is still running
```

**Daemon threads**: background tasks (GC, log flushing, cache cleanup) that shouldn't prevent program exit. Must call `setDaemon(true)` before `start()`.

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
class KitchenStation implements Runnable {
    private final String name;
    private final int cookTimeMs;

    KitchenStation(String name, int cookTimeMs) {
        this.name = name;
        this.cookTimeMs = cookTimeMs;
    }

    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.printf("[%s] Starting...%n", name);
        try {
            Thread.sleep(cookTimeMs);  // simulate cooking
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
            return;
        }
        System.out.printf("[%s] Done!%n", name);
    }
}
```

```java
public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
    long start = System.currentTimeMillis();

    Thread appetizer = new Thread(new KitchenStation("Appetizer", 2000));
    Thread main      = new Thread(new KitchenStation("Main Course", 4000));
    Thread dessert   = new Thread(new KitchenStation("Dessert", 1000));

    // Name them for clearer output
    appetizer.setName("Kitchen-Appetizer");
    main.setName("Kitchen-Main");
    dessert.setName("Kitchen-Dessert");

    // Start ALL — they run concurrently from this point
    appetizer.start();
    main.start();
    dessert.start();

    System.out.println("All stations started. Waiting for completion...");

    // Wait for each to finish
    appetizer.join();
    main.join();
    dessert.join();

    long elapsed = System.currentTimeMillis() - start;
    System.out.printf("All done in %d ms (sequential would be 7000ms)%n", elapsed);
}
```

